(1) Scent Teleportation
People have really developed a nose for the types of thing we=E2=80=99re in=
terested in over here at Not Boring. More people scent us this news than an=
y story in Dose history.=20
Can you smell what Osmo is cooking?
Probably not yet, but soon you might be able to. Osmo Labs, the startup try=
ing to digitize scent, just completed the first teleportation of scent in h=
istory.
Well, teleportation might not be the exact right term. Here=E2=80=99s how i=
t works: Osmo created a "Principal Odor Map" that can predict how a molecul=
e will smell based solely on its chemical structure. This allows them to di=
gitally explore billions of potential molecules and predict their scents wi=
thout physically synthesizing them, greatly accelerating the process of dis=
covering new fragrances and aroma compounds. The POM then generates a formu=
la to recreate the scent, sends the formula to a specialized printer, which=
 then uses a combination of scent ingredients to =E2=80=9Cprint=E2=80=9D th=
e smell. Watch the video above to get a better idea of how it works.
Vision and hearing have been digitized for decades and that digitization ha=
s shaped our digital world experiences. But smell has never been digitized,=
 and its our oldest and deepest sense. Ever wonder why you can precisely re=
member the smell of your mom=E2=80=99s cooking but can recall like two word=
s from that Youtube cooking video you watched? Our sense of smell is just m=
uch, much stronger than our other senses. In fact, it=E2=80=99s directly co=
nnected to the brain's limbic system, where emotions and memories are proce=
ssed.
Digitizing smell =E2=80=94 and thing bringing that ability to digital exper=
iences =E2=80=94 could meaningfully enrich the ways we interact online. Tha=
t=E2=80=99s certainly a big, ambitious goal, but you could certainly imagin=
e Osmo first capitalizing on its breakthrough to disrupt the $30B flavor an=
d fragrance market before creating a world as rich in scents as it is in sc=
enes and sounds.=20
(2) Associations of semaglutide with first-time diagnosis of Alzheimer's di=
sease in patients with type 2 diabetes [ https://substack.com/redirect/a453=
6acb-d7d3-4118-8fce-3fe7d20b39d9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Wang et al in Alzheimer=E2=80=99s Association=20
Semaglutide was associated with 40% to 70% reduced risks of first-time AD d=
iagnosis in T2DM patients compared to other antidiabetic medications, inclu=
ding other GLP-1RAs.
A large study suggests semaglutide may lower Alzheimer's disease (AD) risk =
among high-risk type 2 diabetes patients, because, of course it may. =20
The study reviewed health records of over 1 million patients, and found sem=
aglutide reduced AD diagnosis risk by a whopping 40-70% compared to other a=
ntidiabetic medications, with the strongest effect observed against insulin=
=2E The benefit was consistent across a=
ge, gender, and obesity status, sugges=
ting semaglutide's neuroprotective potential beyond glycemic control.
To be clear, the study does not suggest that semaglutide is a =E2=80=9Ccure=
=E2=80=9D or even a potential therapeutic for Alzheimer=E2=80=99s. What the=
 study does suggest is that semaglutide is more preventative than other dia=
betes drugs, like insulin or metformin, in lowering Alzheimer=E2=80=99s ris=
k.=20
How can this be? The obesity-drug may reduce neuroinflammation and improve =
insulin sensitivity in the brain, which can protect against the buildup of =
harmful proteins linked that have been linked to Alzheimer=E2=80=99s. Addit=
ionally, semaglutide may enhance mitochondrial function and reduce oxidativ=
e stress, both of which are critical in preventing neurodegeneration.
Semaglutide this. Semaglutide that. We=E2=80=99re starting to sound like a =
broken record here. But hey, there=E2=80=99s rarely a week that goes by whe=
re a compelling study on semaglutide=E2=80=99s impact doesn=E2=80=99t drop.=
 And if semglutide keeps dropping the hits, we=E2=80=99ll keep playing them=
=2E
(3) =CF=80 [ https://substack.com/redirect/e49c5842-897b-4ea0-8b39-68998a6e=
ad42?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]0 =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/e49c5842-897b-4ea0-8b39-68998a6ead42?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: Our First G=
eneralist Policy [ https://substack.com/redirect/e49c5842-897b-4ea0-8b39-68=
998a6ead42?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]
Physical Intelligence (=CF=80)=20
In the same way that LLMs provide a foundation model for language, these ge=
neralist robot policies will provide a robot foundation model for physical =
intelligence.
Packy here. One of the questions I think a lot about is why people were so =
much more optimistic about technology in the past than they are today. Some=
 of this is Glory Days Syndrome =E2=80=94 if you read clippings from the ti=
me, people protested every new technology =E2=80=94 but some of it is that =
new inventions made a dramatic and positive difference in people=E2=80=99s =
lives in ways that they could easily measure.=20
Washing machines are perhaps the most famous example. With electric washing=
 machines, the time to do a load of laundry dropped from 4 hours to 41 minu=
tes [ https://substack.com/redirect/cd63f68f-1b5b-4670-96d2-b2baf4781b1b?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Overal=
l, electric appliances cut the average household=E2=80=99s weekly housework=
 from 58 to 18 hours per week. That 40 hour delta just so happens to be the=
 same amount of hours that are in a standard workweek. Jeremy Greenwood and=
 others have made a compelling argument [ https://substack.com/redirect/5cf=
6e123-fc0f-478a-8a4a-7c5f2f581ba5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that electricity and labor-saving household app=
liances led to a dramatic increase in women=E2=80=99s workforce participati=
on.=20
From that perspective, we are so back. Physical Intelligence (=CF=80), whic=
h is building =E2=80=9Cfoundation models and learning algorithms to power t=
he robots of today and the physically-actuated devices of the future,=E2=80=
=9D released its first generalist policy for robots in the form of a blog p=
ost, paper, and videos. Lots of videos. Front and center =E2=80=94 in the b=
log post and the company=E2=80=99s tweets =E2=80=94 they showed off robots =
folding laundry.=20
Folding laundry the way humans would is both an incredibly hard technical c=
hallenge =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cwhile a single t-shirt laid flat on the table c=
an sometimes be folded just by repeating a pre-scripted set of motions, a p=
ile of tangled laundry can be crumpled in many different ways, so it is not=
 enough to simply move the arms through the same motion. To our knowledge, =
no prior robot system has been demonstrated to perform this task at this le=
vel of complexity=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 and a beautifully symbolic one.=20
The promise of machines is to free humans from the tasks we don=E2=80=99t w=
ant to do. Sometimes, that=E2=80=99s a euphemism for =E2=80=9Canything a ro=
bot can do more cheaply than humans,=E2=80=9D but sometimes, it=E2=80=99s j=
ust things we actually don=E2=80=99t want to do.=20
Folding laundry is one of my least favorite things to do. I will leave clot=
hes in the dryer for days to avoid it. I, for one, welcome our new robot la=
undry lords.=20
(4) Obesity Drug Shows Promise in Easing Knee Osteoarthritis Pain [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/f5cc72d9-2f3d-45f7-a521-8dd1de77ef02?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Gina Kolata for The New York Times
A study of 407 people with obesity and knee osteoarthritis found those who =
got semaglutide had an average reduction of 41.7 points on a 100-point scal=
e while those who got the placebo had a reduction of 27.5 points.
And right on cue =E2=80=94 fricken semaglutide out here solving knee pain i=
ssues! The same drug that is basically solving the world=E2=80=99s obesity =
pandemic is also reducing the risk of Alzheimer=E2=80=99s AND reducing knee=
 pain? You said miracle drug, not me!
Researcher=E2=80=99s believe there are two drivers of the reduced pain: sem=
aglutide=E2=80=99s anti-inflammatory properties and its weight-reducing eff=
ects. Makes sense to me. Reducing inflammation and lowering weight your kne=
es need to support would seemingly reduce knee pain. The crazy thing is sca=
le of that pain reduction: patients who received semaglutide reported a nea=
rly 50% reduction in pain=E2=80=94 this level of relief previously only ach=
ievable through costly, painful, and temporarily debilitating knee replacem=
ent surgery.
The. hits. keep. coming.
(5) Meet O=C2=B0 [ https://substack.com/redirect/6f2ff8a2-cb03-4861-afcb-8f=
98a34637c3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]
Neri Oxman for OXMAN
Here=E2=80=99s to a future where products can grow from=E2=80=94and reincar=
nate into=E2=80=94plant matter.
Elliot [ https://substack.com/redirect/86f0c653-286f-428d-9b48-8c8fb042296d=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has b=
een banging the =E2=80=9Cgrow everything with biology [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/d87e0726-bf3f-43be-8910-7d023bd0b7c6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=9D drum for a while, and Ne=
ri Oxman=E2=80=99s company, OXMAN, is making him look like a prophet.=20
Yesterday, the company / lab (hear more about it in her conversation with L=
ex Fridman [ https://substack.com/redirect/19b21142-495f-4666-9005-0cac1ff6=
ae45?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]) =
announced its first product, O=C2=B0: =E2=80=9Ca revolutionary class of bio=
logically programmed, computationally grown, and robotically manufactured s=
hoes and textiles that give biodegradable bioplastics the design that their=
 biology deserves.=E2=80=9D
OXMAN has the talent and resources to bring grown products to mass market. =
In addition to the biology for the materials, they=E2=80=99re using crazy t=
ech like 5 axis 3D printing to bring a new class of products to life.=20
This is what the future should look like. Let=E2=80=99s replace plastics wi=
th biological material printed at scale. As a bonus: no plastics, no microp=
lastics.=20
Bonus: Astro Mechanica Test Fire Videos
You=E2=80=99re going to start hearing a lot more about Astro Mechanica. Whe=
n Not Boring first covered the company in a deep dive [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/494ff55d-6a77-406e-974f-55c469ead2b4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] last April, it was in the earlier=
 stages of pursuing its goal of being able to offer affordable, supersonic =
flights anywhere in the world. The feasibility of that goal hinged on the c=
ompany=E2=80=99s ability to develop a novel jet engine, called the Turboele=
ctric Adaptive Engine. This type of engine combines traditional turbine pow=
er with electric components to adapt fuel efficiency and performance dynami=
cally.
Since then, the company has been proving out its ability to do just that. A=
stro Mechanica recently conducted its first hotfire tests of its Gen 3 turb=
oelectric adaptive engine. That=E2=80=99s a big deal and its attracting som=
e really cool coverage.
From Freethink [ https://substack.com/redirect/b8f0452d-0b11-46a7-8cfd-ff6f=
6d202a3e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]
Jason Carman=E2=80=99s S3 [ https://substack.com/redirect/fa58f6fb-8f1f-410=
a-b893-22d32b713c6a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Astro Mechanica is pulling off some really hard, impressive stuff right now=
 that, if successful is going to benefit each of us in very practical ways:=
 cheaper, faster, better flights.=20
One day, we=E2=80=99re going to be the old people =E2=80=94 probably like 2=
00 or 300 years old if semaglitude keeps it up =E2=80=94 telling our kids a=
bout the days when computers just smelled like metal, we had to fold our ow=
n laundry, and a flight from New York to San Francisco took six hours, each=
 way.=20
When that day comes, remember, you heard it here first.=20
Have a great weekend y=E2=80=99all.
