nces. But smell has never been digitized, and its our oldest and deepest se=
nse. Ever wonder why you can precisely remember the smell of your mom&#8217=
;s cooking but can recall like two words from that Youtube cooking video yo=
u watched? Our sense of smell is just much, much stronger than our other se=
nses. In fact, it&#8217;s directly connected to the brain's limbic system, =
where emotions and memories are processed.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55=
, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Digitizing =
smell &#8212; and thing bringing that ability to digital experiences &#8212=
; could meaningfully enrich the ways we interact online. That&#8217;s certa=
inly a big, ambitious goal, but you could certainly imagine Osmo first capi=
talizing on its breakthrough to disrupt the $30B flavor and fragrance marke=
t before creating a world as rich in scents as it is in scenes and sounds. =
